ce:section.ce:para:
Oil/water IFT is a critical parameter for EOR and, in particular, lower IFT values typically promote more oil production. The effect of N-GQDs size on oil/water IFT and n-heptane/water IFT was analyzed and, similar to the wettability experiments (as shown in Fig. 13
                            and Fig. 14
                           ), 3-N-GQDs significantly decreased the oil/water IFT and n-heptane/water IFT from 16.88 mN/m to 0.975 mN/m and from 50.24 mN/m to 27.87 mN/m, respectively. In accordance with the literature [55], the N-GQDs with the smallest sizes (3-N-GQDs) yielded the lowest IFT values (0.975 mN/m in oil/water systems, and 27.87 mN/m in n-heptane/water systems), while those with the largest sizes resulted in the highest IFT values. Generally, our measurements show that larger N-GQDs promoted larger IFT.

The small sizes of the 3-N-GQDs enabled high incorporations of particles at the oil/water interfaces, which made increasing the N-GQDs concentration from 0.1 mg/mL to 0.5 mg/mL produce prominent reductions in IFT (Fig. 15
                            and Fig. 16
                           ). At high N-GQDs concentrations of 1 mg/mL, the stability was low and aggregation was observed in the base fluid, causing IFT reduction to decrease in accordance with the literature [23,57,58]. Another reason for this phenomenon could be that as N-GQDs concentration increases beyond an optimum concentration (0.5 mg/mL), more N-GQDs accumulate at the oil/water interface and forms a tightly packed layer. This would support a strong interface with ultra-high cohesive forces between oil and water molecules, which would increase the oil/water IFT [53]. These effects could explain the optimal N-GQDs type and concentration (3-N-GQDs at 0.5 mg/mL) lowered the IFT between oil and water, and IFT between n-heptane and water from 16.88 mN/m (DW only) to 0.975 mN/m, and from 50.24 mN/m (DW only) to 27.87 mN/m, respectively.
